explanation:
OS_CHECK_APINAME — This macro/function is invoked directly on timer_name in the target function. Its implementation must be inspected to see whether it performs any string comparisons using memcmp (the MISRA rule target).

OS_CHECK_POINTER — Although unlikely to use memcmp, this macro is invoked for several parameters; include it to ensure its checks do not use memcmp on pointer contents or strings indirectly.

OS_TimeBaseCreate — Called with timer_name. The top-level wrapper may forward the name to internal routines that could use memcmp to compare null-terminated names; the wrapper must be examined.

OS_TimeBaseCreate_Impl — The implementation that actually handles the timer_name (or its validation/registration). This is the most likely place to find memcmp-based string comparisons for the name, so must be checked.

OS_DoTimerAdd — Called with timer_name and responsible for creating the timer object. Its code may compare names (e.g., to detect duplicates) and could use memcmp on null-terminated strings; inspect it.

OS_TimeBaseDelete — If the create path fails the code calls this to clean up. Its implementation may handle name-based lookup or comparisons and could therefore contain memcmp uses that matter for the overall MISRA analysis.
